<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; SHOW; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  HARRY Connick Jr., in black suit, blue shirt, no tie, his thick brown
pompadour held in place with god knows what, enters stage left with a grin and
picks up the hand mike.;   "It's the wrong song, / in the wrong style," he
sings, while behind him faithful companions Shannon Powell on drums and Ben
Wolfe on string bass settle into an easy tempo. He moves to the piano for two
or three choruses that would do Bud Powell proud. The rest of the band comes
roaring in. Harry scats a couple of choruses, returns to the melody, takes it
out. The crowd roars.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CONNICK'S CLOWNING DOESN'T FAZE HIS FAITHFUL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Music Review  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Singer, pianist, songwriter, arranger, bandleader, actor, dancer,
raconteur, Harry Connick Jr., who holds the Orpheum stage through Sunday, is a
wonder, although you have to wonder at the reaction he gets. This is not a
teen-age crowd. Haven't they ever heard an actual singer before? A jazz
orchestra in full cry? A piano player?;   Apparently not. Harry Connick Jr.
can do no wrong for them, although a dispassionate observer would have said
his show Tuesday night contained far too much chatter, far too many lame
jokes, far too much fooling around with the band and not nearly enough good
singing and playing.;   (After "It's All Right With Me" and the intro to
"Don't Get Around Much Any More," his second tune, Connick never went near the
piano except to illustrate a joke, until the last number, when he played
briefly. His encore, alone on stage, was about two minutes of boogie-woogie
piano. He does that well, too.);   They've been calling Connick "the young
Sinatra," but that's silly. Unlike Sinatra, who put the dramatic needs of the
lyric above mere time, Connick is more likely to punch a word here or there
for purely musical reasons. His time is perfect. Vocally, the singer he most
resembles is Bobby Darin.;   He's not a great singer, but he's a very good one
who has the inestimable advantage of having the spotlight on him just now, and
the people who weren't paying any attention to this kind of music when they
were Connick's age (24 as of Wednesday) are paying attention now.;   He's the
latest in a long and honorable line of singer-musicians that includes Matt
Dennis, Buddy Greco, Frank D'Rone and, of course, Nat Cole. You have to range
as high as Mel Torme and Ray Charles to find another singer of Connick's
caliber who also writes big-band arrangements and plays well, too. Connick's
not in their league as a singer, or as a songwriter for that matter, but he
plays better piano than Torme and has a better band than Charles. That's
pretty heavyweight company.;   As an arranger, he has a genius for voicing
brasses, and, as a bandleader, despite his joking-with-the-band shtick, he
demands and gets discipline. His charts can be boorish -- jazz musicians
chanting vocal responses went out with "Pennsylvania 6-5000," didn't it? --
but he is capable of genuine musical wit, noodling "If I Had You" as an intro
to "Don't Get Around Much Any More" and inserting about two bars of "Wildwood
Flower" into "It's All Right With Me.";   He has a nice sense of his own
musical heritage, too. Lead trumpeter Leroy Jones, who contributed several
tight, biting solos, tossed a reference to "Pop Goes the Weasel" into his solo
on "It Had to Be You," causing Connick to growl, "Stop it!" That's a big-band
joke: Thad Jones, then playing lead trumpet for Basie, used "Pop Goes the
Weasel" in his solo on "April in Paris.";   Connick's show at the Orpheum
consists of 15 tunes, counting "Misty," an alto solo for musical director Brad
Leali, but not counting the star's brief encore. It was a nice mix of
standards and originals, including four from his new album, "Blue Light, Red
Light" (due out in two weeks) and his hit "We Are in Love.";   For me, the
best part of the show was "All of Me," played in a slow, steady, almost
ominous 4/4 with Jones and trombonist Lucien Barbarin playing behind him.
Barbarin's solo, using a plunger mute, was spare and elegant, while Jones,
muting with his hand, was on the attack as usual.;   Connick listens happily
when his people are playing. You can sense the mutual respect. "Do I have the
best band in the world, or what?" he cried when "All of Me" ended. Could be.; 
 When he talks too much, when he clowns with the band or has them clown on
their own, when he takes over the drum kit so Powell can dance, when he dances
himself -- he's very graceful, and moves with a kind of pleasing eccentricity,
like Ray Bolger -- when he works the crowd, kidding with latecomers, he's like
a kid with a new toy: all of it, including us. He's having a ball playing with
it, and the audience responds to Connick's pleasure and energy.;   But the
clowning keeps his show from having any pace. It doesn't build, and the last
number, "Just Kiss Me" (from the new album) seems merely more of the same,
only faster and louder.; Harry Connick Jr.; And the Harry Connick Jr.
Orchestra; Where: Orpheum Theater, Market &amp; 8th Street, San Francisco; When: 8
p.m.; Through: Sunday; Tickets: $24.50-$39.50; they're said to be all but
gone, but you can try; Call: (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277  </TEXT>
