<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS --  On Disc:
   Raw Rock and Happy Stuff
   ----
   By Jim Fusilli
</HL>
<DATE>
11/06/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<LP>
   After all the hype is scraped off, the band Guns N' Roses
can at last be assessed by its work. And on its new albums,
"Use Your Illusion I" and "Use Your Illusion II" (Geffen),
the work is very strong. GNR does what it does well:
straightforward, crushing rock; the occasional snide ballad;
wailing guitars; cocky, tough-guy talk. The 30 songs reveal a
tight unit, powerfully pushed by new drummer Matt Sorum and
led by the prototypically raw guitar of Slash. Axl Rose is
more than a competent screech vocalist, though at times on
these recordings he sounds oddly dissociated from the roar of
the band. The lyrics he delivers exhibit a misogyny and
hubris that says more about the writers than they may have
intended. At their best, the albums echo the Rolling Stones'
"Exile on Main Street" in scope.
   The surprise in the 1989 debut album by Tin Machine (EMI)
wasn't in how well the group played, since Hunt and Tony
Sales had anchored a Todd Rundgren band and Reeves Gabriel
had a burgeoning reputation as a guitarist. The surprise came
in how well David Bowie, the quartet's fourth member, worked
within the context of a band. This year's Tin Machine
surprise is just how good its second album is. A little less
raw than the debut recording, "Tin Machine II" (Victory) is a
powerhouse, laden with commanding performances and
well-crafted songs. Bowie seems as elusive as ever -- is he
playing at being a band member? -- and his vocals float
between coy and crude. In "You Belong in Rock &amp; Roll" he
sings, "I love the cheap things you say"; the perfect Bowie
line -- so effete, so Eurotrashy. Gabriel is more controlled
than on the previous effort (too bad) but the Sales brothers
are blustery and fierce; Hunt Sales's vocal on the bluesy
"Stateside" is an unexpected treat.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Emotions" (Columbia), the follow-up to young Mariah
Carey's smash debut album, is more of the same: happy stuff,
plenty of verve; pretty songs; lush, if somewhat electronic
arrangements; and that highly touted voice. Carey excels at
the kind of vocal gymnastics that are so popular among
today's soul-pop warblers; have these vocalists turned the
bliss and fervor felt and expressed by gospel singers into
calculated performance? The question answers itself. Carey
certainly uses her style and her formidable voice to promote
Carey rather than to convey the visceral intent of the
material: Sooner or later, no matter how sweet the song, no
matter how competent her performance, she is going to get up
on her toes and start squealing for dogs. In time, though,
this may change, and with the flair she and colleague Walter
Afanasieff show for writing a pop song, she will be around
long enough to learn to go for the heart rather than just the
applause.
   Even greater stardom beckons for Harry Connick Jr., and
now his vehicle is brassy, ringing, pulsing '40s-style swing
music. On his "Blue Light, Red Light" (Columbia) he pulls out
all the stops; there's big-band swing, small-combo swing,
sentimental blue-ballad swing (and a pretty-boy Connick in
Bruce Weber photos who signs his blushing liner notes
"Swingfully, Harry"). The good news is that it all works. The
album fairly bursts with joyful noise: honey-dripping
arrangements and facile new melodies by Connick and Ramsey
McLean; snappy, urbane lyrics; and soul-filled playing by
trumpeter Leroy Jones and Louis Ford on clarinet. It may be
disingenuous to call a revivalist derivative, so it's best to
say Connick the vocalist is paying tribute to Sinatra, Torme
et al. with his controlled, romantic crooning. Let's hope his
goal -- "to make jazz and swing music loved by the whole
world. And I mean really loved]" -- produces similar
endeavors of this rich quality, from him and others.
   To my knowledge, Garth Brooks's "Ropin' the Wind"
(Capitol) is the first country album to hit the new Billboard
200 chart in the top slot. (The Billboard 200 is a list of
best-selling albums compiled for the magazine by SoundScan, a
company that says it reports on the number of albums sold by
tabulating them at checkout counters.) It's not hard to see
why the album is a hit. It's a winsome collection with
enjoyable songs, and Brooks aims to please in a gentle
country manner: Even his rockers seem to sway. Of course, he
shines with a tender ballad, as with "What's She Doing Now,"
"Lonesome Dove" and the trucker's lament "Cold Shoulder."
   On his new, two-disc set, "Hymns to the Silence"
(Polydor), Van Morrison shouts, "Memories take me way
back/Hank Williams, Louis Armstrong, Sidney Bechet on Sunday
afternoons in winter/and the tuning in of stations in Europe
on the wireless." This, then, is where the muse resides for
this project, wherein Morrison pays unbridled homage to the
sound of his youth -- rhythm &amp; blues, gospel, country, Ray
Charles, Celtic music, '50s jazzy blues -- to a wonderful
result. The music is rich, mature, natural, as are his words:
He paints a Joycean picture of his childhood in Ireland as he
writes of moth catchers working the floodlights, green
meadows and buttercups, picking apples at the side of the
track, rippling streams. "And in between the silence there
was conversation and laughter/And music and singing/And
shivers up the back of the neck," he says with a soft, husky
brogue in "On Hyndford Street." Throughout Morrison is
relaxed, chest swelling with confidence, deep in the pocket,
and in great voice, and the band, led by Georgie Fame on
organ, is expert. With "Hymns to the Silence," Morrison
delivers his best recording in many years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

