<HEAD>JVC Jazz Festival Announced</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bobby McFerrin, minimalist composer Steve Reich
and singers Mel Torme and Cleo Laine will headline three of the
concerts at Carnegie Hall during this year's JVC Jazz Festival.
   Impresario George Wein on Monday announced the lineup for the
festival to be held June 22 through 30. He also paid tribute to
Sarah Vaughan, calling the late singer ``one who belongs in the
Valhalla of jazz greats.''
   Vaughan, a featured performer at the festival in past years,
died April 3.
   ``Our schedule is messed up because we don't have the concert
for Sarah Vaughan,'' Wein said. Concerts for June 29 will be
announced later.
   Opening night will feature the Dizzy Gillespie United Nations
Orchestra at Carnegie Hall. Trumpeter Jon Faddis and the group of
pianist Marcus Roberts, stepping out from Winton Marsalis' combo,
will be guests.
   Miles Davis and the popular group Hiroshima will give two
concerts that night at Avery Fisher Hall. Lionel Hampton and
Orchestra will play in Stamford, Conn.
   Earlier in the evening, ragtime specialist Terry Waldo will play
piano at Weill Recital Hall and the Roy Campbell and William Parker
Duo and Jazz Passengers will play at Equitable Auditorium.
   Those who prefer solo piano can attend the early piano series at
Carnegie's Weill Recital Hall. It will feature Randy Weston, Sir
Charles Thompson, Geoff Keezer, Marty Napoleon, John Lewis,
Abdullah Ibrahim, Mulgrew Miller and Barbara Carroll.
   On Saturday, June 23, Reich and musicians and the World
Saxophone Quartet are at Carnegie; Lee Ritenour and Patti Austin at
Avery Fisher, and a salute to bassist Milt Hinton on his 80th
birthday at Town Hall.
   Sunday finds George Benson and McCoy Tyner at Carnegie and Ray
Charles and Roberta Flack at Avery Fisher. Monday has only early
concerts. Tuesday brings Torme, Laine and John Dankworth to
Carnegie, Milton Nascimento and Wayne Shorter to Avery Fisher and a
salute to guitarist Jim Hall at Town Hall.
   McFerrin, best known for his hit record ``Don't Worry, Be
Happy,'' will appear June 27 with Chick Corea in ``An Evening of
Improvisations.'' Pearl Bailey makes her festival debut that night
at Avery Fisher Hall with trumpeter Winton Marsalis and drummer
Louis Bellson as musical director. At Town Hall that night, Gerry
Mulligan, Ruby Braff and Dick Hyman participate in ``An Evening of
American Song.''
   The Dave Brubeck Quartet will give a free concert Thursday, June
28, at the World Financial Center. ``An Evening with Oscar
Peterson'' will be at Avery Fisher Hall. Stan Getz, with quartet
and sextet, will present 50 years of his music that evening in
Carnegie Hall.
   Saturday brings a Latin jam, with Eddie Palmieri, Ramsey Lewis
and Papo Lucca, to Carnegie. ``A New York City Tribute to Spike
Lee,'' with Nancy Wilson, Ahmad Jamal and Terence Blanchard, at
Avery Fisher, will be a benefit for Jazzmobile, which takes jazz
musicians to city neighborhoods.
   Two concerts that night will be given by Jack DeJohnette, Herbie
Hancock, Dave Holland and Pat Metheny at the Beacon Theater.
   Events away from New York include a noon to 6 p.m. piano
spectacular June 23 and a jazz picnic from 11 a.m. to 6 June 24 at
Waterloo Village in Stanhope, N.J., June 23. On the final Saturday
and Sunday, there will be noon to midnight concerts at the Saratoga
Performing Arts Center, Saratoga Springs, N.Y., and 2 to 11 p.m. at
the Finger Lakes Performing Arts Center, Canandaigua, N.Y.
</TEXT>
