<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO:; Maceo Parker is on tour and back on top.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; CELEBRITY; SHOW; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  MACEO Parker is digging in for a solo on an old James Brown tune. He's onstage
at Elario's Jazz Club, staring straight down the length of his tarnished horn,
holding the bell of the instrument flush against the microphone. He raises his
left eyebrow as he hits a choice, plump note and then, as the solo builds,
starts to sway his hips.;    Now Parker closes his eyes, angles his shoulders,
crouches and jumps from one foot to the other as he yelps through the horn,
playing staccato phrases over and over like a chant, mixing in long, fluid
bebop lines, and turning all these improvised melodies inside out and back
onto themselves.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MACEO PARKER -- SOUL BROTHER NO. 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Parker plays every note with that tart, biting sound of his -- Brown could
never get enough of it -- and with a rhythmic drive that's absolutely
on-the-money. He snakes his way through the stuttering funk beat, the beat
that he helped create with Brown in the 1960s, the beat that made disco
possible, the beat that made rap possible.;    When Parker finishes the solo,
trombonist Fred Wesley and tenor saxophonist Alfred "Pee Wee" Ellis --
compatriots from Brown's old band -- cheer as if they've never heard him play
before. Parker turns to his organist and shouts, "Play that funk, baby. Get it
in your neck.";    Larry Goldings, the organist, is 22. That's how old Parker
was in 1965, when he recorded his first saxophone solo with  Brown, America's
No. 1 Soul Brother, on "Papa's Got a Brand New Bag." In 1968, Parker, Wesley
and Ellis were all in Brown's band when it recorded "Say It Loud -- I'm Black
and I'm Proud." In 1973, Parker and Wesley played on Brown's hit "Doing It to
Death," otherwise known as "We're Gonna Have a Funky Good Time.";    You
remember that one -- the thumping one-chord vamp, the chicken-scratching
guitar, the fat back-beat, Wesley's blow-you-down trombone solo, and how Brown
started screaming for Parker to come to the microphone and play his horn:;   
"Wait a minute!" Brown shouted over the band. "Who'd you say that was over
there? Is that Maceo? Maceo! Hey, brother! Ha ha ha!";    It sounded like the
world's greatest party was happening right there in the studio.;    Then Brown
started to croon:;    "Now Mac -- Mac-ee-o.;    "Brother Maceo! Got to blow!";
   And Maceo Parker stepped to the microphone and raised the temperature
another hundred degrees or so, ripping off one of the more electrifying
saxophone solos in the recorded history of American popular music.; (hbox);   
A quarter-century after this threesome made history, Parker, Wesley and Ellis
are on the road -- the tour stops at San Jose State University today -- and
there's nothing dated or warmed-over about the music.;    Parker's new record
-- No. 2 on the Billboard jazz charts -- is "Roots Revisited." He, Wesley and
Ellis have reached back to play the sort of soulful jump tunes that Ray
Charles and his band made popular in the 1950s. Parker's group performed
Wednesday on "The Tonight Show." This followed Parker's recent recordings with
Living Color and Deee-Lite and concerts with bassist Bootsy Collins -- his
confederate in George Clinton's Parliament and Funkadelic aggregations of the
1970s.;    In the last year, Parker-Wesley-Ellis have toured as the JB (James
Brown) Horns, with a changing cast of characters from the old gang. Parker
also has released a 12-inch hip-hop single called "Let 'Em Out." It's
dedicated to Brown, who was jailed in 1988 after leading a convoy of police
cars on a wild chase in Georgia and South Carolina, supposedly while under the
influence of PCP.;    Parker played with Brown off and on for nearly 25 years
-- including a last-gasp fling before Brown's arrest three years ago. Parker,
sitting in his hotel room one floor below Elario's, recounts all of this. He
is friendly, but a little edgy and distracted. He wears a black fedora pulled
down to the bridge of his nose. When he removes the hat, his eyes dart around
the room -- he's jumpy, like his saxophone playing.;    Parker, born in
Kinston, N.C., 47 years ago, remembers his uncle Bobby Butler, who used to
play drums in a band called the Blue Notes. During intermissions, Butler would
let his nephews have their turn -- Parker was on saxophone, his younger
brother Melvin was on drums and older brother Kellis, now a Columbia
University Law School professor, played trombone. They called themselves the
Junior Blue Notes and covered hits by Lloyd Price, Little Willie John and the
Drifters. "I'm trying to think," Parker says, "did we do some James Brown
stuff back then? Maybe we did 'Try Me.' And we did 'Shout' by the Isley
Brothers.";    Parker and Melvin attended college for a year or two. But then
Brown spotted Melvin playing in a club in Greensboro, N.C., and offered him a
job. The brothers quit school and plotted to sell themselves to Brown as a
package -- difficult, Maceo says, inasmuch as "James was too crazy about
Melvin." But Maceo fast-talked his way into a job as Brown's new baritone
saxophonist, even though he had barely played the big horn in his life.;   
That was in 1964. Ellis joined Brown's band in 1965, and Wesley in 1968.;   
In the late 1960s, when Ellis was the band's musical director, Brown had the
hardest working band in show business -- on the road 50 weeks a year. The
shows were exhausting for everyone, and their effect on the crowd was
hair-raising.;    Parker calls Ellis and Wesley to his hotel room to talk
about their old boss.;    Wesley: "It was pandemonium.";    Parker: "Before I
even got in the group, I had gone to see the show and that was one of the
things that astonished me. 'Cause I was still young and I didn't understand
how people who were supposed to be of stature in the community -- school
teachers and good church-going folks -- could be screaming and falling down in
a frenzy and carrying on. That was what was more interesting to me -- the
audience rather than the music. And I said, 'What is this thing he's got?' I
said, 'What the devil is it?' He knew how to work the audience.";    Wesley:
"And the show was so well put-together. I'd seen people like Bobby Bland and
Ray Charles -- but they just played the tunes. James had the lighting and the
sound and the costumes. He'd come out and sing 'If I Ruled the World.' Then
he'd go away and later he'd come back and it was the git-down thing. I was
amazed.";    Brown's concerts were built around the same principle as a gospel
show -- raising the temperature higher and higher. Parker served as back-up
emcee and back-up comic. He also played back-up to the guy who removed the
ermine cape from Brown's shoulders: "We used to call that 'throwin' the cape,'
" Parker remembers, laughing. "I must've done everything but front-office
work.";    It was a grueling, pressure-filled gig and Brown could be an
unreasonable boss: "I was part of the group and I seemed to be an integral
part of the show," Parker says, "so I thought, 'Why am I not compensated
more?' Because a lot of people were coming to the shows to see me play. I've
come to the reality that I have to make my own bed. James Brown's another
artist that I may work with at some time, but it'll never be as boss-employee
again. 'Cause I'm well into my own thing.";    In March, Parker's band will
tour Europe and record a follow-up album -- tentatively titled "Mo' Roots." A
week from Saturday, Parker will appear on "Saturday Night Live" with Bootsy
Collins and Deee-Lite. He is busy.;    "They'd have to come up with some real
big money to have me put this on the back burner again," he says. "It would
have to be almost unbelievable money."; (hbox);    Parker is finishing his
second set at Elario's Jazz Club in La Jolla.;    The band is playing "Soul
Power." There's a man in the audience named Anthony Young. Twenty years ago,
he used to watch his mother put on her hot pants for a night on the town: "I'd
say, 'Where are you going.' She'd say, 'I'm going to see James Brown.' I
remember my mother saying, 'You know, that James Brown -- he's all right. But
does he have a horn section!";    And now Young is hollering:;    "Blow Fred!
Blow, man! Blow!;    "Blow your horn, Maceo!";    There's pandemonium at
Elario's.;    The show breaks up a little before midnight, and Parker exits,
shaking hands with folks in the audience on his way out. He goes downstairs to
his room, changes clothes, grabs some coffee and stays up for hours, talking
about Brown, gabbing on the phone with the old friends who keep calling, and
finally retiring around 3 a.m.;    At 9 a.m., the band piles into its rented
van for the drive to Los Angeles. Wesley drives. Parker sits beside him. Ellis
is in the seat behind. Wesley pops a tape into the cassette player. It's a
1968 recording of a Brown concert in Dallas. Brown had a 15-piece big band at
the time, arrangements courtesy of Ellis who wears a small, delighted smile
now as the music begins.;    "Do you hear that?" shouts Parker, an astonished,
bug-eyed look coming across his face. He's punching the air in rhythm with the
horn section.;    "You were on tenor?" he asks Ellis.;    "No, I was alto. You
were tenor," Ellis answers.;    Brown sings "If I Ruled the World," his voice
high and light. It's the voice of a young man.;    Then Brown starts to mix it
up. He leads the crowd in "Say It Loud (I'm Black And I'm Proud)," then segues
into "Kansas City," which has a fantastic horn arrangement, played super-fast
and as tight as can be. The memories are all coming back. Parker, Wesley and
Ellis are anticipating each musical turn of phrase, pointing out all the
intricacies of the arrangements, laughing, marveling at how good it sounds 23
years later. Ellis leans forward in his seat so he's in a line with Wesley and
Parker and now all three are bobbing their heads in time with the music.;   
And then Parker's voice comes over the speakers -- he was emceeing the show,
it seems -- telling the crowd to cheer for "the young man who you made the No.
1 Soul Brother In America!";    And then Brown sings "Cold Sweat" and starts
to plead:;    "Maceo! I want you to play!;    "Maceo! I want you to play!";   
And there's the sound of Maceo's horn, getting down, snaking its way through
the stuttering funk beat. And Maceo Parker leans back in his seat in the van
and listens, as he heads north to the next gig.;  Maceo Parker; And Roots
Revisited, featuring Fred Wesley and Pee Wee Ellis;     Where: San Jose State
University Student Union Amphitheater, 211 S. 9th St., San Jose.;    When:
Noon today.;    Tickets: Free admission. (408) 924-6260.;    Where: Slim's,
333 11th St., San Francisco;    When: Saturday at 9 p.m.;    Tickets: $13 in
advance, $14 at the door. (415) 621-3300.;    When: 7:30 p.m. and 9:30 p.m.
Sunday;    Where: Kuumbwa Jazz Center, 320-2 Cedar St., Santa Cruz.;   
Tickets: $13.50 in advance, $15 at the door. (408) 458-2313.  </TEXT>
