<TEXT>  BOB SEGER; "The Fire Inside"; (Capitol; all formats); (star)(star); At one
time -- a long time ago -- Bob Seger was content to play that old-time rock
'n' roll. Nothing fancy; nothing frilly. He simply went for and with the gut.
And if he didn't have inspiration, he certainly had enthusiasm.;   But for the
past 10 years and more, Seger has dispensed with even that and released
records that have been sturdy, stolid and middle-of-the-road boring.;   Thus
it is with "The Fire Inside.";   There is a strapping Middle America feel to
this record, with its allusions to Ray Charles R&amp;B ("Always in My Heart") and
Cajun ("Sightseeing") and, yes, rock 'n' roll ("Which Way").;   But for the
most part, the record is dizzyingly dull, with Seger and "guests" Joe Walsh
and Bruce Hornsby and others going about their work like a group of fitters on
the Ford assembly line.;   He does approximate his old feel on one or two
songs -- such as "She Can't Do Anything Wrong." And the title cut does pound
away in the good old way. But the rest of the time, Seger's sappy singing is
proof that he no longer has the fire inside that is necessary to make that
old-time rock 'n' roll.; -- Harry Sumrall; MARIAH CAREY; "Emotions";
(Columbia; CD, cassette); (star)(star) 1/2; For almost a decade, it's been
altogether too easy to dismiss the entire mainstream pop-soul genre as a
wasteland of trite, vapid musical mush -- creatively bankrupt and increasingly
irrelevant since the advent of rap and alternative rock. Mariah Carey might
not be able to erase that perception, but at the very least her music is going
to force a lot of people to reconsider the viability of the genre.;   Last
year, Carey's debut album stunned a listening public that had been drugged
into a catatonic state by years of Lionel Richie &amp; Co. releases. In February,
her incredibly poised Cinderella-at-the-ball performance at the Grammys
charmed millions worldwide. Now, her sophomore release should prove she's no
one-hit wonder, but a major star who's going to be with us for quite some
time.;   "Emotions" is by far a tougher, sexier and flat-out better product
than Carey's ultra-glossy debut album. Rather than swathing her talents in
layers of cotton-candy instrumentation, Carey and co-producer Walter
Afanasieff decided to take the less-is-more approach -- and it works
beautifully. Carey's incredible eight-octave voice drives this disc. From the
four-star gospel-tinged ballad "If It's Over" (co-written by Carey and Carole
King) to the Donna Summer-esque dance-floor ditty "Make It Happen," this is a
pure power play.;   Most of this material is predictable saccharine drivel
(Robert Clivilles and David Cole, the production wizards behind the notorious
C&amp;C Music Factory, have a hand in all the dance-floor tracks), but listening
to Carey take a mediocre song and just whip it around is a sublime pleasure.
The woman has real soul and an instinctive sense of phrasing. She certainly
owes more of a stylistic debt to Tina Turner, Chaka Khan and Diana Ross than
she does to Whitney Houston and other contemporaries. I'm no fan of pop-soul
balladry, but I came away from "Emotions" with one overwhelming impression --
"Dang, has that girl got a set of pipes or what?"; -- David Plotnikoff; PROCOL
HARUM; "The Prodigal Stranger"; (Zoo; CD; cassette, LP); (star)(star); Procol
Harum -- now there's a name out of the past. Remember their great hits,
including "Conquistador," "A Salty Dog" and, of course, "A Whiter Shade of
Pale"?;   After a 15-year absence, the group has reformed and is touring the
United States. (They'll stop at San Francisco's Palace of Fine Arts on
Thursday). Unfortunately, "The Prodigal Stranger" sounds so anonymous it could
be a new release by, say, Steve Winwood.;   Part of the problem is lead singer
Gary Brooker, whose vocals on their '60s classics were so haunting, and who
now sounds as uninspired as the aforementioned Winwood -- as on "Perpetual
Motion.";   And the once-distinctive guitar of Robin Trower (who will be
replaced on the tour by Tim Renwick) is barely noticeable. (Two other early
Procol members, keyboardist Matthew Fisher and lyricist Keith Reid, also are
on board for the reunion. A new rhythm section features bassist Dave Bronze
and former Big Country drummer Mark Brzezicki.);   There are a couple of
exceptions, however. "(You Can't) Turn Back the Page" recalls the group's
earlier ballads with Fisher's swirling organ melodies and Brooker's soulful
vocal. Brooker also does a splendid job leading the multitude of voices on
"Holding On.";   But those moments are far too few. Maybe they should call
this "A Paler Shade of Procol."; -- Steve Marinucci; Jazz; THE VERY BIG CARLA
BLEY; BAND; (WATT/ECM; CD, cassette); (star)(star)(star)(star); In 1981, Bley
told me she was through breaking musical rules, that she wanted her band to
sound like Basie's. It was only half in jest: Her arrangements, renowned for
their humor, rapid shifts in time and texture, have begun to sound like
Ellington's.;   Like Duke, Bley writes memorable melodies and creates lush
tonal beds for soloists. Like Charles Mingus, she likes to pull the rug out.
And those broken rules, like a "wrong" chord from Thelonious Monk, have a way
of sounding great when our ears catch up.;   I'm delighted to report that
she's now caught up with herself. After two bizarrely out-of-character nods to
commercialism, "Night-Glo" and "Sextet," both small bands and both
forgettable, she made the lovely "Duets" with electric bassist Steve Swallow.
And in 1989, she stormed back with "Fleur Carnivore," a 15-piece band recorded
live in Copenhagen.;   The Very Big Band isn't live, but it's memorable. Taped
in Germany in October, it boasts 18 musicians, including most of the soloists
from "Fleur": Lew Soloff, trumpet; Andy Sheppard, tenor; Wolfgang Puschnig,
alto; and Gary Valente, trombone.;   There's a 15 1/2-minute suite, "United
States," a wonderfully quirky "Strange Arrangement," a church-meeting "Who
Will Rescue You?," the nursery rhyming "All Fall Down" and a Latin explosion,
"Lo Ultimo.";   Everything works. The writing is elegant, the voicings superb
(especially the use of the oboe and Swallow's bass guitar). The solos swing,
Sheppard in particular. I do miss the tuba from the old days, though.; --
James V. Murray; NEW RELEASES; Pop/rock; (box)The Red Hot Chili Peppers 
"Blood Sugar Sex Magik" (Warner Bros.);   (box)John Prine  "The Missing Years"
(Oh Boy);   (box)Smithereens  "Blow Up" (Capitol); R&amp;B; (box)Queen Latifah 
"Nature of a Sista" (Tommy Boy); Country/Bluegrass; (box)Ricky Skaggs  "My
Father's Son" (Epic)  </TEXT>
