<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Television: The Duke and the Queen </HL>
<AUTHOR> Robert Goldberg </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to video biography, no one's doing it better than "American Masters" (Mondays, 9 p.m. ET, on PBS). 
Now in its third season, this lively series has profiled American treasures from Buster Keaton to Truman Capote, from George Gershwin to Isaac Bashevis Singer. 

   This summer, the series (executive produced by Susan Lacy) returns with another all-star lineup of creative artists: film maker William Wyler, photographer Andre Kertesz, the Algonquin Round Table, painter Diego Rivera, sculptor Augustus St. Gaudens. 
It also offers musical royalty -- the Duke of jazz and the queen of soul. 

   Tonight and next Monday night, "American Masters" will present a two-part retrospective on Edward Kennedy Ellington: "A Duke Named Ellington" (produced by Terry Carter, written by Leonard Malone). 
Creator/arranger of more than 2,000 pieces -- including "Satin Doll" and "Take the A Train" -- Duke Ellington is a mammoth figure in American music. 
Perhaps more than any other single person, he shaped jazz as we know it today. 

   Early in the 1920s -- the jazz age -- Duke Ellington came to New York to make his mark. 
Getting a gig up at Harlem's Cotton Club, he and his band backed the song-and-dance numbers. 
The advertisements for the all-white audience labeled their sound "jungle music," but Mr. Ellington was soon turning out the most sophisticated and delicate of harmonies: "Mood Indigo," "East St. Louis Toodle-oo" and "Creole Love Call." 

   For this suave bandleader and his satin sound, the 1930s and 1940s were the glory years. 
He and his orchestra became world famous, even starring in Hollywood movies. 
But by the '50s, big bands were out, be-bop was in, and no one wanted to hear from the Duke. 

   It was the toughest challenge of Mr. Ellington's career. 
Revitalizing his sound and moving into "modern" jazz, he took the 1956 Newport Jazz Festival by surprise with "Diminuendo and Crescendo in Blue." 
That performance was a breakthrough, and it led to a long and rich final creative phase, including extended works -- ballets and sacred pieces. 

   Duke Ellington was said to "play his orchestra like an instrument," and interviews with band members Clark Terry, Ben Webster and Jimmy Hamilton -- and Mr. Ellington himself -- show how the Duke created works for his specific musicians. 
We learn about Ellington as musical inventor -- how he experimented with unusual "cluster" voicings. 
And best of all, we see minutes and minutes of wonderful performance footage of the Ellington band in Europe, never before shown here. 

   But if "A Duke Named Ellington" gives us a solid sense of Ellington the musician, it offers almost no picture of Ellington the man. 
Over two hours, you get desperate to know -- what was he like? 
The film doesn't say. 
The few clues we get don't add up to much. 
"I never saw Duke lose his temper." 
Cut to "Duke got mad at Johnny Hodges once -- they were arguing -- Duke just picked him right up." 
Cut to "Duke and Johnny, they were just {close as can be}." 

   Issues of race and racism would seem to be central to the Duke Ellington story, but film maker Carter touches on them only enough to tantalize us, no more. 
Musician Herbie Hancock says Mr. Ellington "deserves as much or more attention as George Gershwin, and he didn't necessarily get it." 
An interesting charge -- and one that's never developed. 

   Mr. Ellington gets a wry, if cryptic, last word, when a gauche interviewer asks him about "the music of your people" in one clip: "My people? 
Which are my people? 
Piano players? 
Those who aspire to be dilettantes? 
Those who attempt to produce something? 
Those who appreciate Beaujolais?" 

   Aretha Franklin probably wasn't one of Duke Ellington's people, but from "Aretha Franklin: The Queen of Soul" (Aug. 22), it's hard to tell. 

   Raised by her father, a powerful Detroit minister, the Reverend C.L. Franklin, Aretha grew up surrounded by music in the church and at home, where Sam Cooke, Jackie Wilson and Oscar Peterson would drop by. 
At the age of 14, she was out performing with her father on the gospel circuit. 
By 17, she had two children. 
By 20, she was a pop superstar. 

   If you want to find out more about Aretha, you'd better go to the library, because this documentary (written by Nelson George and produced by Kirk D'Amico) won't tell you. 

   Sure, there are celebs like Whitney Houston, Ray Charles and Keith Richards mouthing celeb statements. 
George Michael says "She's the best." 

   So many questions are left unanswered. 
Allusions to tragic relationships, illegitimate children and nervous breakdowns -- all sorts of weird and unhappy stuff -- fly by without explanation. 
What can you expect from a film that opens with ". . . in soul, there's only one queen. 
Her name -- Aretha Franklin." 
Cut to Ms. Franklin proclaiming, "In 1962, I was crowned the queen of soul." 
Puff piece? 
Did anyone say, puff piece? 

   But, as in the Ellington portrait, the music here redeems all sins. 
From "Respect" to "Dr. 
Feelgood," from "I Never Loved a Man" to "Chain of Fools," Aretha belts and squalls and soars through these tunes. 
If you like this music -- so profane, so sacred -- you won't be disappointed by this documentary, whatever its flaws. 

   But the "American Masters" programs -- at their best -- offer both the art and the artist. 
Last year's look at Isaac Bashevis Singer, for example, was a wonderful, glowing portrait, crammed to the edges with vivid details about the man and his work. 
The Duke and the queen deserve nothing less. 

</TEXT>
