<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; AWARD; RESULT; NAME; RECORD; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN the 1991 volume in the annals of pop history is finished, Chapter One
will be titled "Miracle on Sixth Avenue: The Grammys Wake Up.";    A canny
57-year-old music-industry warhorse and a bright-eyed 20-year-old
superstar-in-training turned the tide at the 33rd annual Grammy Awards in New
York City's Radio City Music Hall Wednesday night. For the first time in
recent memory, talent and achievement won big over commercial clout and
soporific garbage. Granted, it was a partial victory, but a victory
nonetheless.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GRAMMYS DO THE RIGHT THING
MONEY TAKES A BACK SEAT TO TALENT AS A GRIZZLED
VETERAN AND A BUDDING STAR DESERVEDLY DOMINATE
THE AWARDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
Additional information attached to the end of this article.
See related stories pages 1C and 10C of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In case it sounded too far-fetched, let me repeat. The good guys won. You
may cheer quietly now.;    Four-decade veteran Quincy Jones almost made a
clean sweep of the seven categories he was nominated in. His only loss was to
Angelo Badalamenti in best pop instrumental performance. His six Grammys raise
his career total to 25 -- the most for any pop artist.;    Backstage, a
positively glowing Jones told the assembled throng: "I've won 25 now, but I've
also lost 57 times. And believe me, I don't take it for granted." Jones, who's
been a hidden power behind hundreds of artists from Dizzy Gillespie and Ray
Charles to Michael Jackson and rapper Big Daddy Kane, proved convincingly that
experience can win over youth and cashbox muscle. Essentially, Jones was
honored for mustering a busload of his famous friends and creating an album,
"Back on the Block," that was wide-ranging enough to be honored in every
category except polka. He should have won the Grammy for best casting.;   
Twenty-year-old Mariah Carey, on the other hand, earned her two Grammys the
old-fashioned way: with solid songwriting and singing. The newcomer took best
new artist and best pop vocal performance/female, beating veteran heavyweights
Bette Midler and Whitney Houston on the latter.;    The big losers during the
six-hour marathon of congratulations were the pop trio Wilson Phillips, who
won none of the four categories in which they were nominated; Sinead O'Connor,
who won only the most minor of the four categories she ran in; and Phil
Collins, who was one for eight for the night. Granted, Collins won the one
that counts: record of the year. Vanilla Ice walked away empty-handed.;    The
Grammys are a unique and ornery beast. It's not a pure popularity show like
the vacuous American Music Awards. Nor is it a pure celebration of cashbox
clout. And never, never, has it been a good arbiter of artistic merit.;    The
annual rite -- played out for a live audience of 6,000 and a television
audience in 60 countries -- is a separate reality glimpsed through the eyes of
the 6,000-plus voting members of the National Academy of Recording Arts &amp;
Sciences. And, what a wacko world it is:;    A world in which a deceased
Leonard Bernstein can compete against (and lose to) Oakland-born rap superstar
M.C. Hammer in the best music video category. A world in which Neil Young's
song "Rockin' in the Free World" can be nominated for best rock vocal
performance -- even though it doesn't appear on his 1990 album. A world where
Jimmy Stewart, John Kennedy Jr. and Kyle MacLachlan of "Twin Peaks" can lose
the best spoken-word recording to George Burns (at 95, the oldest nominee).;  
 The tempest in a teapot over boycotting nominees Sinead O'Connor and Public
Enemy was not a major factor in the show. It was as if the Clash told
Buckingham Palace they wouldn't be stopping by for dinner. Bloody big deal.
The militant rap group Public Enemy, which had boycotted the awards because
the rap segment in which they were competing was not televised, lost to Quincy
Jones and a posse of his friends during the first minute of the ceremony.;   
O'Connor's absence was good for a dark laugh when the Celtic singer stole the
best alternative music performance from the Replacements. The hapless
presenter managed to mumble the stock "I'm sure she wishes to express great
thanks to the members of the Academy" before bursting out laughing.;    That
wasn't the only bug that was dismissed as a laughing matter Wednesday night.
Host Garry Shandling joked about the Milli Vanilli-gate fallout in his opening
monologue. If the Academy is still stung by last year's fiasco with the
lip-syncing Eurotrash boy-bimbos, it didn't show.;    The first major-league
communal groan of the night came early in the telecast as the camera flashed
across the smirking mug of Vanilla Ice as he reacted to M.C. Hammer's
performance. His what-me-worry attitude didn't last long. Moments later,
Hammer bested him in the best rap solo performance category. Too bad the
camera wasn't there to watch Ice's pompadour wilt like a week-old head of
lettuce.;    Backstage, Hammer cradled his three trophies and tried to put the
best face on the so-called rivalry between him and Ice. "I don't blame him at
all. His record company saw an opportunity to paint this as a black and white
thing. A good boxing match. After I stopped laughing, I said, 'Oh? what's
next?' Really -- I don't blame him at all.";    In addition to the three
awards he received, Hammer was a savvy pick for album of the year, but it was
swept away by Jones.;    Schmaltz did win in a major category, as Julie Gold
bagged the top songwriter's award, song of the year, for "From a Distance,"
the song made into a Desert Storm cry of hope by Bette Midler.;    Carey
looked and sounded like a natural winner from the start. She was sexy,
composed and in excellent voice as she sang "Vision of Love." Partly, she was
impressive because many other of the performance segments contained material
so limp it couldn't stand up with the aid of a crane.;    Backstage, when
asked if she considers herself a pop artist or an R&amp;B artist, she replied
coolly: "I consider myself a singer/songwriter. I don't think I should
categorize myself as pop. I'm grateful for any nomination.";    As a group,
Bay Area artists did not fare well. Palo Alto native Michael Hedges lost in
the best new age performance category to Mark Isham. Peninsula sax legend Stan
Getz lost to Quincy Jones in the best jazz fusion performance category and
lost to Oscar Peterson in best jazz instrumental performance soloist. Redwood
City boogie king John Lee Hooker, Novato slide guitar ace Roy Rogers and San
Francisco bluesman Taj Mahal lost to B.B. King in the best traditional blues
recording category. Bobby McFerrin lost in the jazz vocal performance/male
category to wunderkind Harry Connick Jr.;    Some high points in the
six-hour-long day's journey into night (only 17 of the 78 categories were
awarded on the air): Shandling did an excellent job with an almost-impossible
assignment, keeping the show loose and flowing through the long, awkward
telecast. Bob Dylan's blistering unscheduled performance just before he
received a lifetime achievement award from Jack Nicholson was one for the
history books. (Lifetime achievement awards also went to Marian Anderson, John
Lennon and Kitty Wells.);    Jazz guitarist Stanley Jordan put on a
mind-boggling, dead-on-perfect one-man recital that included playing two
electric guitars at once. You had to see it to believe it.;    "Robert
Johnson: The Complete Recordings," the best historical work on pre-rock to
come out in years, won in its category -- best historical album.;    For every
high point, there were corresponding glitches, atrocities and unspeakable
acts.;    Even the great blues diva Ruth Brown couldn't save the first dozen
awards of the long, pre-telecast portion. Thanks to a flurry of pre-telecast
no-shows (most notably M.C. Hammer, who won a pair of early awards), virtually
the entire first hour of the show was deader than an old Christopher Cross
eight-track tape. Tracy Chapman's leaden, lethargic and off-key rendition of
John Lennon's "Imagine" was a major wince event.;    The most tasteless moment
-- and there were plenty of nominees in that category -- came during Billy
Idol's mysterious opening skit to his "Rock the Cradle of Love" performance in
which he appeared to molest a winsome teen who came to his door.;  RECORD OF
THE YEAR;    "Another Day in Paradise,";    Phil Collins; ...;    ALBUM OF THE
YEAR;    "Back on the Block,";    Quincy Jones; ...;    SONG OF THE YEAR;   
"From a Distance,";    Julie Gold;    (Bette Midler); ...;    NEW ARTIST;   
Mariah Carey; ...;    POP VOCAL PERFORMANCE, FEMALE;    "Vision of Love,"
Mariah Carey; ...;    POP VOCAL PERFORMANCE, MALE;    "Oh Pretty Woman,";   
Roy Orbison; ...;    ROCK VOCAL PERFORMANCE, FEMALE;    "Black Velvet,"
Alannah Myles; ...;    ROCK VOCAL PERFORMANCE, MALE;    "Bad Love,";    Eric
Clapton  </TEXT>
