<HEAD>ALL THE ELEMENTS: In Search of Roots</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurice White is thinking a lot about the past
these days. He has someone checking out his family tree _ he knows
his great-grandmother lived in New Orleans, and he wants to go back
further, much further.
   Musically, it's the same story. Earth, Wind &amp; Fire's new album,
``Heritage,'' is another kind of family tree, the tone set by
``Takin' Chances'' and its refrain of ``No risk, No gain.''
   Sly Stone is on it, so is M.C. Hammer, and tributes are paid to
Fats Waller and Charlie Parker. The music features jazz, funk,
rhythm and blues and rap, with time out for one of Philip Bailey's
sweet ballads.
   ``The album was a germ in my mind,'' White, the band's founder
and producer, said in a telephone interview from Los Angeles.
``It's very interesting watching it evolve and come to fruition. It
starts as an idea, and all of a sudden it's a giant thing.
   ``I was thinking, first of all musical heritage, the things we
had drawn from. And we wanted to bring to our fans' attention
things to appreciate, things to be proud of.''
   The LP has 17 songs and runs for an over an hour. The title
track features rappers The Boys. Hammer, whose album ``Please
Hammer Don't Hurt `Em'' has topped the charts, gives raps on two
songs, ``Wanna Be the Man'' and ``For the Love of You,''
   Stone contributes his best James Brown shout to ``Good Time,''
and the brief instrumental ``Interlude: Bird'' features a saxophone
solo influenced by Parker.
   ``The things that really thrill me about the record was having
the opportunity to work with other artists who I had admired from a
distance. Sly Stone I really had only met casually. He was one of
my early influences, he and Ray Charles,'' White said.
   ``My son, Kibran, listens to M.C. all the time _ besides being
hip to what's going on in the streets, M.C. has a positive message
for young people. So it was a way of bringing back two eras
together and getting back on the cutting edge.''
   This is actually the second edition of Earth, Wind &amp; Fire.
White, a former session musician at Chess Records, formed the first
one in the late 1960s; it soon broke up. So White gave it another
try: same name, new members.
   ``I made sure that they understood it was going to be a long,
rocky road,'' recalled White, who recruited Bailey, brother Verdine
White on bass and six others. ``I was looking for people who had
dedication and integrity to the music. Growth takes a long time. I
still have growing pains.''
   Originally a little known jazz group, Earth, Wind &amp; Fire didn't
click until 1975 and their sixth album, ``That's the Way of the
World.'' The fast-paced chant ``Shining Star'' was a No. 1 single,
its story of every man's uniqueness an update of Stone's
``Everybody Is a Star.'' It appealed to just about all audiences.
   Earth, Wind &amp; Fire has since had six double platinum albums and
won seven Grammys, but White isn't satisfied with the band's
reputation as a ``crossover'' act. Listen to him and you wonder
about the chorus of the new album's title song: ``Just be proud of
your land, where your blood comes from.''
   European audiences are more challenging than American ones, he
says. In the states, they just want to hear the hits _ including
``Boogie Wonderland,'' ``September'' and ``Let's Groove'' _ while
Europeans respond to White's more ambitious outlook.
   ``I think in a lot of cases we have been logged as being a black
group musically and that's it. They look at their faces, and say,
`They're black and therefore they do this kind of music.'
   ``In Europe, they're more open to the music and more open to the
culture. They're inquisitive. They don't understand anything about
the culture and so they try to investigate and have an open mind.''
   White and the band push on, surviving a temporary split in 1984,
and adjusting to a music scene that never stops changing. ``We'll
go on `till we drop,'' he says. A recent visit to the Berlin Wall
reminds him how much there is to write about, and thoughts of their
world tour make him anxious to get back on the front line.
   ``The tour will be about musical heritage, artistic heritage,
racial heritage. We have something now which I think the whole
globe is gravitating to, and that is the world beat,'' he said.
   ``With the opening up of all these different countries in
Eastern Europe, we have a lot more people to reach. What we're
gearing up towards is a great world community.''
